00:51:59,240 --> 00:52:09,240
early on when I was talking to people, what I 
would say is that I think that there is a certain  

537
00:52:09,240 --> 00:52:22,400
amount of psychological safety in allowing the 
feedback loop to stay long because really of two  

538
00:52:22,400 --> 00:52:33,880
main factors. One is that, look, if I was early 
into Uber and now I'm a celebrity investor or  

539
00:52:33,880 --> 00:52:40,920
something, I don't really want to know if I'm good 
or not. Do I? Right? I don't really want the world  

540
00:52:40,920 --> 00:52:45,240
to know that. I mean, if I'm good, that's great. 
But it feels like they already believe that I'm  

541
00:52:45,240 --> 00:52:49,840
good because I happen to be early into Uber.
So since people already think I'm good,  

542
00:52:49,840 --> 00:52:57,680
I'm just losing to that decision, psychologically 
speaking. Not investment quality speaking,  

543
00:52:57,680 --> 00:53:04,880
but psychologically speaking. Okay, so here's 
the problem though. Why was I early into Uber?  

544
00:53:04,880 --> 00:53:16,760
Did I have an insight into a real pain point in 
a developing market, blah, blah, blah? Or did  

545
00:53:16,760 --> 00:53:21,120
my buddy start Uber and I was like, "Sure, I'll 
give you some money?" Right? I mean, obviously,  

546
00:53:21,120 --> 00:53:26,320
I'm talking about the extremes here, but we don't 
actually know what the decision quality was,  

547
00:53:26,320 --> 00:53:31,160
right? All we know is that you had a good result 
and given that you had a good result and people  

548
00:53:31,160 --> 00:53:38,400
think very highly of you, what are you going to 
gain? Right? So it's so nice to just let that  

549
00:53:38,400 --> 00:53:44,480
feedback loop sit there and allow people to 
have the opinion of you. That is really nice,  

550
00:53:44,480 --> 00:53:51,560
feels good, right? And not actually find 
out the answer because why would I want to?
 

551
00:53:51,560 --> 00:53:56,920
Unless you're really super focused on decision 
quality, then you would want to do that. So that's  

552
00:53:57,600 --> 00:54:07,080
part of the psychological safety. And what that 
goes to is, the real core of it is that it's very,  

553
00:54:07,080 --> 00:54:12,560
very difficult for human beings to 
deal with feeling wrong in the moment,  

554
00:54:12,560 --> 00:54:19,960
even if it helps them in the long run. It's 
just hard. And the tighter the feedback loop,  

555
00:54:19,960 --> 00:54:24,320
the more that you risk finding out you are 
wrong in the short run. Now that helps you  

556
00:54:24,320 --> 00:54:28,800
to learn and improve your decision-making if 
you're focused on it and you're good at it,  

557
00:54:28,800 --> 00:54:31,800
right? That's going to help you. And then 
in the long run, you're actually going to  

558
00:54:31,800 --> 00:54:36,320
do better. But human beings are notoriously 
good at trading off the long run just to feel  

559
00:54:36,320 --> 00:54:41,120
good in the short run. That's why we're all 
eating chocolate and cupcakes and stuff that  

560
00:54:41,120 --> 00:54:48,720
we know is bad for us because it feels good.
And so much of our decision-making is trying  

561
00:54:48,720 --> 00:54:54,840
to advance this positive self-narrative and 
the idea that yeah, we're going to have a  

562
00:54:54,840 --> 00:55:01,680
more positive narrative ourselves in five years 
if we do some stuff. Most of us are like, "No,  

563
00:55:01,680 --> 00:55:08,120
I don't really want to make that trade. I'd 
rather just feel good now", and I can use the  

564
00:55:08,120 --> 00:55:18,080
fact that we are living in power law, under the 
influence of power law. I can use that to just  

565
00:55:18,080 --> 00:55:24,720
confirm a lot of things that I wish to believe 
that are true of me. And if you take that away  

566
00:55:24,720 --> 00:55:30,840
from me and you take the uncertainty away from 
me, it's going to be really hard. And I will tell  

567
00:55:30,840 --> 00:55:34,560
you that's what I love about both Renegade 
and First Round is that they're just like,  

568
00:55:34,560 --> 00:55:40,480
I want to know. It would be such a horror for me 
to think that I was making good decisions when I  

569
00:55:40,480 --> 00:55:47,360
actually wasn't. And that's what really matters 
to me and I think that it's just so special.
 

570
00:55:47,360 --> 00:55:51,600
Hearing all this makes me want to be an LP in 
First Round. Not that they would let me in there,  

571
00:55:51,600 --> 00:55:55,400
but just knowing that you're in there futzing 
with everything and the way they're thinking is  

572
00:55:56,400 --> 00:56:00,200
really inspiring. I'm curious if you 
could share an example of anything that  

573
00:56:00,200 --> 00:56:05,600
they tweaked as a result of this analysis 
that you did and how they evaluate.
 

574
00:56:05,600 --> 00:56:11,840
Well, first of all, let me just say they didn't 
really record a lot about their decisions when I  

575
00:56:11,840 --> 00:56:16,960
first came in. They voted and they had a record 
of the vote so they knew who said yes and who  

576
00:56:16,960 --> 00:56:23,720
said no, but they didn't have a lot of other 
information. So the first thing that happened  

577
00:56:23,720 --> 00:56:30,000
was just that. Okay, what do we really think 
is the way that you would model whether you  

578
00:56:30,000 --> 00:56:37,680
should invest or not invest in? Very broadly, you 
would say you're reading the market, the team,  

579
00:56:37,680 --> 00:56:43,120
the founder, the product broadly. We're going to 
make sure that those opinions aren't just like  

580
00:56:43,120 --> 00:56:47,760
it's good or it's bad, but it's on a scale of 
one to seven so that we can actually get some  

581
00:56:47,760 --> 00:56:53,640
precision and some spread among the partners in 
terms of, say, strength of market. We're going to  

582
00:56:53,640 --> 00:57:00,320
make sure that we have shared definitions of those 
things, which you'd be surprised people don't.
 

583
00:57:00,320 --> 00:57:04,480
So when I am thinking about market and market 
quality, I might be thinking about something  

584
00:57:04,480 --> 00:57:08,120
very different than you. So we want to make 
sure that we have a shared definition of that,  

585
00:57:08,120 --> 00:57:12,600
and that's reflected in something that we would 
call mediating judgments, which are judgments  

586
00:57:12,600 --> 00:57:17,920
that you make related to market prior to actually 
judging what you think of the market in general.  

587
00:57:17,920 --> 00:57:26,280
So you could think of something like competitive 
landscape, so you would judge that. So that turns  

588
00:57:26,280 --> 00:57:30,160
into what these mediating judgments are, 
which is basically an implied definition.
 

589
00:57:30,160 --> 00:57:33,720
So you create that, and then you also think about 
what are the forecasts that are important. One  

590
00:57:33,720 --> 00:57:37,560
thing that you already know is you're going to 
forecast the probability the company funds at  

591
00:57:37,560 --> 00:57:45,760
Series A. So that was a huge change, just a very 
different way of making decisions. What we've  

592
00:57:45,760 --> 00:57:51,920
been able to do with that now because I've been 
there for five years is we now can actually look,  

593
00:57:51,920 --> 00:57:57,280
say the partnership as a whole, and look 
at these ratings that they're making of  

594
00:57:57,280 --> 00:58:02,200
the component pieces of parts of how they're 
modeling, like what makes a good investment,  

595
00:58:02,200 --> 00:58:05,320
these forecasts that they're making.
And we actually know how these companies  

596
00:58:05,320 --> 00:58:12,520
have now unfolded. So in the simplest sense, we 
know whether hundreds of companies have funded at  

597
00:58:12,520 --> 00:58:19,800
Series A or not. And now, we can actually look 
and say, how good are the partners at actually  

598
00:58:19,800 --> 00:58:25,640
forecasting this thing? Right? Are they random? 
Are they better than random? And we actually know  

599
00:58:25,640 --> 00:58:31,920
that and we can feed that back to them so that 
they can understand their own accuracy around  

600
00:58:31,920 --> 00:58:40,320
these pieces of the decision because the fact 
is that whatever a seed investor says to you,  

601
00:58:40,320 --> 00:58:44,120
whether that company is going to fund at 
Series A is part of their decision. It's  

602
00:58:44,120 --> 00:58:49,080
included in the decision. So they're making 
that forecast whether they make the forecast  

603
00:58:49,080 --> 00:58:54,080
explicitly or not. So what we're saying over at 
First Round is let's make it explicit because  

604
00:58:54,080 --> 00:58:58,000
you're doing it implicitly anyway, and then we 
can actually start to look at your accuracy.
 

605
00:58:58,000 --> 00:59:03,480
We can now feed that back to you and let you 
know how accurate you are, which will then  

606
00:59:03,480 --> 00:59:11,840
help you to become more accurate, right? We can 
also look, because we know in any given vintage  

607
00:59:11,840 --> 00:59:15,480
what are the best companies or what are the worst 
companies. Remember, we're having people do these  

608
00:59:15,480 --> 00:59:20,320
ratings on a scale of one to seven of say the 
quality of the market, and we can look across  

609
00:59:20,320 --> 00:59:28,040
the partnership and say, "Look, Lenny, when you 
think the market is great, how does that map onto  

610
00:59:28,040 --> 00:59:34,560
how well the company is doing in the future? 
When you say the market is terrible, how well  

611
00:59:34,560 --> 00:59:41,280
does that map onto how that company is doing, how 
that company ends up doing in the future?" And I  

612
00:59:41,280 --> 00:59:47,720
can come to you and I can say, "Oh, Lenny, by the 
way, your judgments about market are amazing."
 

613
00:59:47,720 --> 00:59:54,120
You know a good market when you see one and it's 
really mapping on in a great way onto how that  

614
00:59:54,120 --> 00:59:59,880
company unfolds, but you're not so great with 
founder, or maybe you're great across the board,  

615
00:59:59,880 --> 01:00:05,960
or maybe you're not. So we can now start to 
give people, we can give the partners insight  

616
01:00:05,960 --> 01:00:10,080
into their own decision-making, not only to 
allow them to improve the decision-making,  

617
01:00:10,080 --> 01:00:16,480
but also to allow them to understand not to over 
index on certain things that maybe aren't as  

618
01:00:16,480 --> 01:00:22,640
predictive as an example for them. We also can 
change the rubric based on the evidence now.
 

619
01:00:22,640 --> 01:00:27,960
So the first version of the rubric is always 
taking the intuitions of the partners and making  

620
01:00:27,960 --> 01:00:37,080
those explicit, but then we can start to loop 
those back together and understand, well, maybe  

621
01:00:37,080 --> 01:00:41,240
this thing that the partners thought was important 
actually isn't predictive across any partner. For  

622
01:00:41,240 --> 01:00:46,560
example, we can start to develop the rubric based 
on the data. These were all things that weren't  

623
01:00:46,560 --> 01:00:53,360
possible because prior to that, if I had come in 
and said, "Well, let's look at decision quality",  

624
01:00:53,360 --> 01:00:59,320
how would I do that? I mean, I have no idea why 
people were... I just know whether they said  

625
01:00:59,320 --> 01:01:04,760
yes or no. And so it's very difficult to them to 
start to do some really serious refining of the  

626
01:01:04,760 --> 01:01:10,640
decisions if I don't have that information.
I desperately want to know which partner it  

627
01:01:10,640 --> 01:01:13,240
makes the best decisions. I know 
you're not going to share them.
 

628
01:01:13,240 --> 01:01:19,360
No, I'm not going to. The partnership as a whole 
is excellent as we know. And this is what I will  

629
01:01:19,360 --> 01:01:25,240
tell you is that all partners have strengths and 
all partners have weaknesses, and they're not  

630
01:01:25,240 --> 01:01:29,920
perfectly overlapping, which is wonderful, right? 
I mean, that's one of the things. It's like what's  

631
01:01:29,920 --> 01:01:35,880
really wonderful, and I think it shows the power 
of why would you have more than one person having  

632
01:01:35,880 --> 01:01:42,400
input into a decision, is some people are very 
strong on rating a particular aspect of market, or  

633
01:01:42,400 --> 01:01:49,560
some people are very strong on rating a particular 
aspect of the founder. There's overlap and then  

634
01:01:49,560 --> 01:01:55,320
there's things where Todd is uniquely great at 
something, or Josh is uniquely great at something,  

635
01:01:55,320 --> 01:02:00,200
or Bill is uniquely great at something. So that's 
a wonderful thing about it is that everybody has  

636
01:02:00,200 --> 01:02:05,360
strengths and everybody has weaknesses and they're 
not perfectly overlapping. So this is where you  

637
01:02:05,360 --> 01:02:10,640
can see getting that spread of opinions and really 
understanding, breaking that decision down into  

638
01:02:10,640 --> 01:02:21,800
its component parts really shows you the value 
of diverse opinions as input into a decision.
 

639
01:02:21,800 --> 01:02:25,160
I could talk about this thread forever. Maybe let 
me just ask one more question just because I'm  

640
01:02:25,160 --> 01:02:29,680
super curious. Is there anything surprising that 
stands out, that came out of this analysis so far?  

641
01:02:29,680 --> 01:02:34,640
Just like, oh wow, maybe market isn't as important 
as we thought or this person is amazing at-
 

642
01:02:34,640 --> 01:02:42,200
Yes. So I think just generally speaking, when 
you're creating the initial decision rubric,  

643
01:02:43,040 --> 01:02:46,720
there are things that people are really pounding 
the table about that they think is especially  

644
01:02:46,720 --> 01:02:55,320
important in making a decision. And one of the 
things that we found is that sometimes their  

645
01:02:55,320 --> 01:03:01,040
intuition was absolutely right. The thing that 
they were pounding the table about is incredibly  

646
01:03:01,040 --> 01:03:09,800
predictive, not just for them but other partners. 
But sometimes it's not at all predictive,  

647
01:03:10,640 --> 01:03:16,080
and these are equal table-pounding situations. 
So let's say you're pounding the table about  

648
01:03:16,080 --> 01:03:22,400
something, sometimes the thing you're pounding 
at the table about is predictive for you and  

649
01:03:22,400 --> 01:03:26,120
for all the other partners that it's actually 
quite predictive about how the company does.  

650
01:03:26,120 --> 01:03:29,440
But sometimes when you're really 
pounding the table about something,  

651
01:03:29,440 --> 01:03:33,360
it's not just that it's not predictive for the 
other partners, it's not predictive for you.
 

652
01:03:33,360 --> 01:03:36,640
And I think that what's really important to 
understand about this, and this is why it's so  

653
01:03:36,640 --> 01:03:43,480
incredibly necessary in improving decision quality 
to take what's implicit and make it explicit,  

654
01:03:43,480 --> 01:03:49,800
is that our intuition is sometimes right and 
sometimes wrong. It's not that intuition is crap  

655
01:03:49,800 --> 01:03:55,200
and your intuition is just completely wrong, I 
mean obviously, that can't be true. We would die,  

656
01:03:55,200 --> 01:04:00,680
right? So your intuition is sometimes 
right, but it's also sometimes wrong.  

657
01:04:00,680 --> 01:04:07,680
And if you don't make it explicit, then 
you don't get to find out when it's wrong.
 

658
01:04:07,680 --> 01:04:13,760
You don't get to find out when it's off base, 
and that's a disaster. So that's the thing that  

659
01:04:13,760 --> 01:04:20,920
I think is really interesting is that you have 
equal vehement and confidence that this particular  

660
01:04:20,920 --> 01:04:27,960
factor is really important. And sometimes it is 
and sometimes it isn't. And it's so surprising  

661
01:04:27,960 --> 01:04:36,800
because we're talking about people who are true 
experts who are great, and I think that we all  

662
01:04:36,800 --> 01:04:43,840
just have intuition about intuition, right? 
You just intuit that if they're so amazing,  

663
01:04:43,840 --> 01:04:50,440
clearly their intuition about what's important 
would have to be good, but not necessarily.  

664
01:04:50,440 --> 01:04:55,640
That's the thing, not necessarily. Yeah, I think 
that was probably the most exciting thing.
 

665
01:04:56,600 --> 01:04:59,520
Keeping it mysterious, but I 
still appreciate you sharing.
 

666
01:04:59,520 --> 01:05:03,160
Well, I have to keep it mysterious.
Yes, I understand.
 

667
01:05:03,160 --> 01:05:08,600
I can't give away the trade secrets.
I wanted to touch on a different framework that  

668
01:05:08,600 --> 01:05:12,520
I've heard a lot of companies actually using, and 
something that comes up in product a lot is this  

669
01:05:12,520 --> 01:05:18,200
idea of pre-mortems, which is essentially think 
ahead of time what might go wrong. Can you talk  

670
01:05:18,200 --> 01:05:22,000
about this? Because I think that it's something 
that's easy to implement, really powerful,  

671
01:05:22,000 --> 01:05:28,880
and a lot of people are actually doing this.
Yes, okay. So a pre-mortem is great, but only  

672
01:05:28,880 --> 01:05:35,320
if you attach a pre-commitment with it. So I 
just want to be super clear about that. What  

673
01:05:35,320 --> 01:05:39,520
you find with pre-mortems, this actually work. 
I actually did this work with Maurice Schweitzer  

674
01:05:39,520 --> 01:05:45,080
and Linnea Gandhi, who are both at Penn. 
Then when you have people do pre-mortems,  

675
01:05:45,840 --> 01:05:51,160
it generally doesn't actually change their 
plan very much or it changed their behavior.  

676
01:05:51,160 --> 01:05:54,840
So I think that we have the feeling that if you 
do a pre-mortem and you think what are the ways  

677
01:05:54,840 --> 01:06:02,000
that things might go wrong, that that's going to 
change your plan, but probably not unless you're  

678
01:06:02,000 --> 01:06:07,760
specifically using it for that purpose and you 
say, "Okay, we're going to do this, but let's  

679
01:06:07,760 --> 01:06:11,680
think about how we might change our plan in light 
of this information." But I think what's actually  

680
01:06:11,680 --> 01:06:18,080
more important than that is what a pre-mortem 
allows you to do is to set up kill criteria.
 

681
01:06:18,080 --> 01:06:27,120
So kill criteria are just a set of signals that 
you might see that would tell you that it's time  

682
01:06:27,120 --> 01:06:35,240
to pivot or stop because once we actually 
launch something, we're very, very slow  

683
01:06:35,240 --> 01:06:41,560
to decide to quit. I'm sure that everybody has 
felt that way before. Things go on way too long,  

684
01:06:41,560 --> 01:06:45,840
even like they're over budget and you've blown 
the timeline. And when you finally shut it down,  

685
01:06:45,840 --> 01:06:50,480
you realize you should have done it a lot earlier. 
And this is true across the board because of a  

686
01:06:50,480 --> 01:06:55,000
variety of biases. The most well-known, and 
probably the biggest influence is something  

687
01:06:55,000 --> 01:07:00,240
called sunk cost, which is that feeling, but 
then I'll have wasted all the time and effort  

688
01:07:00,240 --> 01:07:05,160
that I've put into this already. So it's taking 
into account what you've put in in the past and  

689
01:07:05,160 --> 01:07:11,080
deciding whether to continue on in the future. 
So what we want to do is actually just get  

690
01:07:11,080 --> 01:07:17,160
better at that thing. So understanding that 
when you've gotten to the pre-mortem process,  

691
01:07:18,200 --> 01:07:22,600
you probably are going to launch it, 
like it's probably going to be the case.
 

692
01:07:22,600 --> 01:07:29,240
Use the pre-mortem to set up kill criteria. So 
I'll give you an example from a sales team that  

693
01:07:29,240 --> 01:07:36,520
I worked with. Basically, I sent them out 
a prompt, all the IC is a prompt that was,  

694
01:07:36,520 --> 01:07:43,600
imagine that you got a lead through an RFP or 
RFI and you worked on it for six months. And now,  

695
01:07:43,600 --> 01:07:47,960
it's six months later and the deal is dead. 
Looking back, you realized they were early  

696
01:07:47,960 --> 01:07:52,400
signals that that was going to be the case, what 
were they. So this is a pre-mortem. What are the  

697
01:07:52,400 --> 01:07:57,840
things that you saw that would tell you that 
this was going to go south? And they came up  

698
01:07:57,840 --> 01:08:04,320
with all sorts of ideas. Notice this doesn't mean 
they're not going to start off pursuing the lead,  

699
01:08:04,320 --> 01:08:10,800
right? But they saw, they came up with all sorts 
of signals. So I'll just give you three of them.
 

700
01:08:12,600 --> 01:08:18,120
The RFP RFI was clearly written with a competitor 
in mind, so they felt that was a very bad signal  

701
01:08:18,120 --> 01:08:23,840
that was probably going to go badly. Another one 
was the customer didn't want to demo, they only  

702
01:08:23,840 --> 01:08:29,080
wanted to talk about price. Obviously, that's 
quite bad. And another one was after the first  

703
01:08:29,080 --> 01:08:34,160
few meetings, they couldn't get a decision maker 
in the room, right? So it was a much longer list  

704
01:08:34,160 --> 01:08:39,320
than this, but those are three. So for each of 
those, that now becomes a kill criteria if I see  

705
01:08:39,320 --> 01:08:47,000
this thing and now you attach an action with it. 
So in the case of price, they actually just said,  

706
01:08:47,000 --> 01:08:51,120
"We should kill it." If they literally don't 
want to demo and they're only asking about price,  

707
01:08:51,120 --> 01:08:56,600
they're just trying to beat up somebody else 
on price like we're a box-checking exercise.  

708
01:08:56,600 --> 01:08:59,760
So there, they just said, "We're going to kill 
it. We're not going to pursue the deal anymore."
 

709
01:08:59,760 --> 01:09:06,160
So this is great because salespeople will pursue 
deals forever and leadership is like, "Well,  

710
01:09:06,160 --> 01:09:09,760
why did you stop pursuing that deal?" And they 
get in trouble for it. So this is going to help  

711
01:09:09,760 --> 01:09:15,640
with that problem, right? In the case of the 
RFP RFI was written with a competitor in mind,  

712
01:09:15,640 --> 01:09:20,720
they have an action associated with that as well, 
which is ask them directly if they're working with  

713
01:09:20,720 --> 01:09:25,360
a competitor and how far down the road they are, 
depending on the answer you would kill or pursue.  

714
01:09:26,200 --> 01:09:29,400
In the case of we couldn't get a decision 
maker in the room, offer up executive  

715
01:09:29,400 --> 01:09:35,800
alignment at the next meeting. And if they 
say sure, great. And if they say no, kill.
 

716
01:09:35,800 --> 01:09:40,640
So that's actually what I feel is the 
best use of a pre-mortem is to say,  

717
01:09:40,640 --> 01:09:46,920
I'm going to try to figure out what those signals 
are along the way that things are going badly. And  

718
01:09:46,920 --> 01:09:52,200
now instead of just hoping that when I see 
those signals, I actually act rationally,  

719
01:09:52,200 --> 01:09:57,200
which is a hope that it will not come true. That's 
why there's many people who climb Everest in the  

720
01:09:57,200 --> 01:10:04,040
middle of a blizzard, even though they shouldn't 
be doing that. Use the pre-mortem to now create  

721
01:10:04,040 --> 01:10:10,400
structure around those signals that you've 
spotted and commit to actions that you're  

722
01:10:10,400 --> 01:10:15,640
going to take if you see those signals. And I 
think that's the best use of a pre-mortem.
 

723
01:10:15,640 --> 01:10:20,080
That's really helpful. And it's interesting how 
many of your examples come back to just of a  

724
01:10:20,080 --> 01:10:24,440
framework that you often talk about, which is 
make it explicit what is implicit. There's another  

725
01:10:24,440 --> 01:10:29,080
example that the First Round example is a great 
example of that where it's just, here's all our  

726
01:10:29,080 --> 01:10:32,393
assumptions, they just make them actually explicit 
and just shows how much [inaudible 01:10:32].
 

727
01:10:32,393 --> 01:10:37,240
Right, then you can examine them. You can 
examine them, people can discuss them,  

728
01:10:37,240 --> 01:10:42,880
you can figure out if they're wrong or right or 
whatever. It's like, I want to be very clear,  

729
01:10:42,880 --> 01:10:53,240
I'm not anti your gut or your intuition. I 
think it's probably sometimes pretty good. I  

730
01:10:53,240 --> 01:10:58,400
just want you to make it explicit, that's all.
Okay. So we didn't have time to get into quitting,  

731
01:10:58,400 --> 01:11:02,520
which is your more recent book. Maybe we'll 
do a follow-up episode specifically thinking  

732
01:11:02,520 --> 01:11:05,143
about quitting, but let me just ask-
It's my fault because my answers are long.
 

733
01:11:05,143 --> 01:11:06,680
It's my fault.
I apologize to everybody.
 

734
01:11:06,680 --> 01:11:10,880
No apology is necessary. We'll have plenty of 
time in the future, hopefully. Well, let me just  

735
01:11:10,880 --> 01:11:15,320
ask one question. I found this one quote from you 
where you said you should assume that if you're  

736
01:11:15,320 --> 01:11:20,440
thinking about quitting, it's already probably 
past the time that you should have quit. Do you  

737
01:11:20,440 --> 01:11:26,400
still believe that? Is that generally a good rule 
of thumb? And just any takeaway, tip, lesson on  

738
01:11:26,400 --> 01:11:34,760
quitting as our one question on quitting?
So the data is pretty strong that by the time  

739
01:11:34,760 --> 01:11:43,080
you quit, it's probably long after the [inaudible 
01:11:37]. And it's really just because, look,  

740
01:11:43,080 --> 01:11:47,160
when we start things, we're starting 
things under difficult circumstances,  

741
01:11:47,680 --> 01:11:52,920
which come from the uncertainty of the decision 
to start something. So when we start something,  

742
01:11:52,920 --> 01:11:56,800
luck is going to have an influence on the outcome, 
which obviously, we have no control over because  

743
01:11:56,800 --> 01:12:00,880
luck isn't in our control. And then there's also 
hidden information. So what happens is that after  

744
01:12:00,880 --> 01:12:05,240
the fact, we know that we're going to learn new 
information and it can make it very hard to start  

745
01:12:05,240 --> 01:12:11,920
things because we want to be more sure than we 
actually need to be. It's why Bezos has the 70%  

746
01:12:11,920 --> 01:12:16,760
role to try to roll people back and be willing to 
accept that uncertainty in the starting decision.  

747
01:12:16,760 --> 01:12:23,600
Now the good news is that when you learn that new 
stuff and the new stuff that you learn is, "Ooh,  

748
01:12:23,600 --> 01:12:28,080
if I had known this, I wouldn't have started 
it", you have the option to quit generally.
 

749
01:12:28,080 --> 01:12:32,440
So that's the good news. The bad news is 
that the same difficulties that apply to  

750
01:12:32,440 --> 01:12:36,040
the decision to start apply to the decision 
to stop. In other words, we're making that  

751
01:12:36,040 --> 01:12:41,200
decision under uncertainty as well. So we're 
not going to know for sure whether it would've  

752
01:12:41,200 --> 01:12:48,360
turned out well or poorly unless we continue 
to do the thing that we already started. And  

753
01:12:48,360 --> 01:12:53,800
we don't like to walk away from things unless 
we know for sure. So as Richard Thaler put it,  

754
01:12:53,800 --> 01:12:59,120
most people won't quit until it actually isn't 
a decision. In other words, the whole thing is  

755
01:12:59,120 --> 01:13:07,640
blown up, the startup has no money, or you're up 
on Everest and the blizzard is literally upon you  

756
01:13:07,640 --> 01:13:14,560
and you're stuck in it. Or I think as he said, 
until you've fallen in the crevasse already, then  

757
01:13:14,560 --> 01:13:19,960
you'll make the decision to quit because then you 
know how it was really bad. So people generally,  

758
01:13:19,960 --> 01:13:26,560
for example, don't quit their jobs until they 
feel they have no other choice or relationships  

759
01:13:26,560 --> 01:13:35,200
or projects or products that they're developing, 
it all applies because we want to know for sure.
 

760
01:13:35,200 --> 01:13:40,800
And then on top of that is the fact that there 
is this issue of sunk cost, which is when we walk  

761
01:13:40,800 --> 01:13:44,760
away, we feel like we'll have wasted everything 
that we've already put into what we're doing. But  

762
01:13:44,760 --> 01:13:49,360
of course, waste is a prospective problem, not 
a retrospective one, even if we treat it like a  

763
01:13:49,360 --> 01:13:54,520
retrospective one because it's the prospective 
one. Well, if you wouldn't start this today,  

764
01:13:54,520 --> 01:13:58,000
then that means that everything that you're 
putting into this going forward is the actual  

765
01:13:58,000 --> 01:14:03,800
waste, right? But we do that all the time. We go 
forward with things that we ought not to be going  

766
01:14:03,800 --> 01:14:08,320
forward with because we're trying to protect the 
resources that we've already sunk into it in the  

767
01:14:08,320 --> 01:14:13,120
past. Then there's other issues that have to do 
with, for example, endowment, the ownership over  

768
01:14:13,120 --> 01:14:18,080
the things that we've built. This is particularly 
bad in product because we're building things.
 

769
01:14:18,080 --> 01:14:23,000
And once we build things, we own them. And once 
we own them, we don't want to give them up and  

770
01:14:23,000 --> 01:14:27,280
we actually value them more highly than identical 
things that we don't own. And then there's issues  

771
01:14:27,280 --> 01:14:32,000
of internal and external validity, which is 
really just a fancy way to say your identity.  

772
01:14:32,000 --> 01:14:36,680
How do other people view you? How do you view 
yourself? Do you feel like you failed? And what  

773
01:14:36,680 --> 01:14:42,480
that means is that by the time, there's so many 
biases against stopping that by the time you're  

774
01:14:42,480 --> 01:14:47,280
actually even thinking about quitting, it's 
probably already past the time that you ought  

775
01:14:47,280 --> 01:14:52,000
to have quit. But we'll still continue on 
until we know for sure we didn't have any  

776
01:14:52,000 --> 01:14:56,800
choice because here's the thing. When you walk 
away from something and someone's like, "Hey,  

777
01:14:56,800 --> 01:15:01,560
why'd you stop that?" And you're like, "Oh, I had 
no choice" and you tell them everything that went  

778
01:15:01,560 --> 01:15:05,400
wrong and, nobody's going to question you.
They're going to be like, "Oh, well,  

779
01:15:05,400 --> 01:15:12,600
it sounds like you put in your best effort." But 
if you walk away early, people are like, "What?"  

780
01:15:12,600 --> 01:15:18,080
So just quickly, I'll tell you I think just one 
of the best stories of this that I've got in my  

781
01:15:18,080 --> 01:15:26,320
pocket here. Let me pull it out before the end. 
So Stewart Butterfield creating a product called  

782
01:15:26,320 --> 01:15:35,800
Glitch, and Glitch is a massive multiplayer online 
world-building cooperative game. Releases it, this  

783
01:15:35,800 --> 01:15:42,480
is in the aughts, and it's like a huge hit with 
the critics. It's Monty Python meets Dr. Seuss,  

784
01:15:42,480 --> 01:15:49,040
it's an incredible whatever. They're getting 
tons and tons of great word of mouth and PR not  

785
01:15:49,040 --> 01:15:53,880
doing any paid marketing. They have incredible 
investors in Andreessen Horowitz and Accel,  

786
01:15:53,880 --> 01:16:00,040
they have $6 million in the bank and they 
5,000 have diehard users, meaning users who  

787
01:16:00,040 --> 01:16:08,720
use the game who play over 20 hours a week.
The issue is that customer acquisition was a  

788
01:16:08,720 --> 01:16:15,680
beast that for every one person who was playing 
over 20 hours a week, there were between 95 and  

789
01:16:15,680 --> 01:16:24,800
99 people who came for five minutes and left. So 
obviously, this is a customer acquisition problem,  

790
01:16:24,800 --> 01:16:30,600
which everybody knows. So they make an agreement 
in 2012 that they're going to do paid marketing,  

791
01:16:30,600 --> 01:16:36,000
which they do for six weeks. And during that 
six weeks, their acquisition of new users,  

792
01:16:36,000 --> 01:16:42,640
it's growing like six to 7% week over week, which 
is amazing. And at the end of that six weeks,  

793
01:16:42,640 --> 01:16:48,600
this is November of 2012, at the end 
of that six weeks, that Monday morning,  

794
01:16:48,600 --> 01:16:53,600
Stewart Butterfield writes a note to his investors 
and co-founders and says, "I woke up this morning  

795
01:16:53,600 --> 01:17:01,080
with the dead certainty that Glitch was over."
Now notice nobody would do this in this case,  

796
01:17:01,080 --> 01:17:06,640
right? But this is what happened is that the 
issue is that you really have to see is this  

797
01:17:06,640 --> 01:17:11,680
worthwhile or not? Would I start this today? 
That's a forecast of the future, right? And  

798
01:17:11,680 --> 01:17:16,400
what he did was some back-of-the-envelope math, 
and he said, "Look, if we continue to acquire  

799
01:17:16,400 --> 01:17:21,120
customers at the weight that we've been acquiring 
them at the cost that we've been acquiring them,  

800
01:17:21,120 --> 01:17:26,760
it's going to be 31 weeks until we break even." 
But that's an absurd assumption because customer  

801
01:17:26,760 --> 01:17:31,480
acquisition costs, it's going to go up. Cap has 
to rise because we're going to saturate the core  

802
01:17:31,480 --> 01:17:36,760
gaming market, so it's got to rise. So what he 
realized at that point was that this was not  

803
01:17:36,760 --> 01:17:41,600
a venture scale business, and he was in this 
for a venture scale business. So even though  

804
01:17:41,600 --> 01:17:45,640
nobody else saw that he was supposed to shut it 
down, he saw he was supposed to shut it down.
 

805
01:17:45,640 --> 01:17:48,720
And not only that, he saw that he was supposed 
to shut it down for his employees who were  

806
01:17:48,720 --> 01:17:54,200
working for equity, and he had now realized 
that the equity wasn't worth their time and  

807
01:17:54,200 --> 01:17:58,960
that it wasn't fair to them to keep going 
with it. So he shuts it down. Obviously,  

808
01:17:58,960 --> 01:18:04,080
that feels... Who does that? Right? And he will 
actually tell you that he knows he should have  

809
01:18:04,080 --> 01:18:10,800
shut it down before the marketing push, but he 
needed the marketing push to prove it to himself  

810
01:18:10,800 --> 01:18:16,640
that he was seeing the future clearly. Now, the 
code to this story just quickly is two days later,  

811
01:18:16,640 --> 01:18:20,440
he's like, "Well, I'm a startup guy. I want to 
start something", and he's got this internal  

812
01:18:20,440 --> 01:18:24,560
communication tool that his team is using in 
order to develop this product that everybody  

813
01:18:24,560 --> 01:18:28,840
loves. And he says, "Actually, they really like 
that. Maybe that should be the next product."
 

814
01:18:28,840 --> 01:18:33,840
So he goes and talks to the investors, they roll 
their money over into that. And that thing, which  

815
01:18:33,840 --> 01:18:39,200
had no name at the time, now gets a name which 
is searchable log of all company knowledge, which  

816
01:18:39,200 --> 01:18:44,680
is Slack. And so I think this is the important 
thing to realize is that we get so focused on,  

817
01:18:44,680 --> 01:18:49,880
"But what about everything that I've put into 
it?" When what we forget is that when you're doing  

818
01:18:49,880 --> 01:18:56,320
something, there's not just the cost of doing 
something that's not worthwhile that's direct,  

819
01:18:56,320 --> 01:19:02,040
but there's also the cost of not being able to 
devote your attention to other opportunities  

820
01:19:02,040 --> 01:19:07,600
that might be available to you. And as smart as 
Stewart Butterfield is, he couldn't see Slack  

821
01:19:07,600 --> 01:19:15,440
until he quit Glitch. And that is a true cost that 
he would've born of continuing with Glitch. If he  

822
01:19:15,440 --> 01:19:21,440
had continued with Glitch, Slack would not 
be something that we're all using today.
 

